\begin{slide}{Attack Landscape}
\begin{description}
\item[Extranet] The networked world outside your network with which your users require access. Generally not under your control.
\item[Intranet] The networked world inside your perimeter, which is under your control
\item[Host] A node within a network, consisting of servers, PCs, routers, etc.
\item[Perimeter] The network devices and systems which are connected to at least one extranet as well as an intranet. Generally
                 these act as monitors, gateways, and service providers
\item[Endpoint] A type of {\em host} which is the connection between a user and your {\em intranet}
\end{description}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}{Network Architecture}
\begin{itemize}
\item Web servers providing content to customers, installed at perimeter
\item Extranet not "layer 3"-routable by non-Perimeter Intranet devices
\item HTTP proxy server installed at Perimeter to provide users with Extranet connectivity
\item Endpoints installed in Intranet
\item Remote users may connect to a VPN system, installed at the Perimeter, which connects their
      endpoint to the Intranet network
\item Perimeter devices are "layer 3"-routable by all Intranet hosts, and vice-versa
\end{itemize}
\end{slide}

